## Justification A — dist-manifest composition

Principle applied literally: «универсально целиком или не едет». A path
ships only if EVERY instance needs ALL of it. framework/, runtime/,
distribution/, docs/, knowledge/ are universal by construction; qroky.sh,
CHANGELOG, README, LICENSE, MANIFEST, .gitignore are the product's face
and entry. Everything else is factory (products/, decisions/, TASKS.md,
launch files, roles/, RELEASE-v0.1.md) — it moves to lab, not to users.
Directories ship WHOLE (no sub-path carve-outs) — a manifest of
exceptions would rot; content curation inside shipped dirs is CEO's
parallel HUMAN-TASK, flagged in RESULT (advisor review file, heartbeat
logs).

## Justification B — sparse-checkout over manifest-filtered copy

Mandate offered the choice; chose git sparse-checkout (non-cone):
- The vendored framework stays a REAL tag-pinned git checkout, so the
  entire existing self-update channel (fetch, tag checkout, status/stash
  dirty-check, PROVENANCE) is untouched — a filtered copy would have
  forced a parallel update mechanism and duplicated ATOM-106 logic.
- The SAME manifest read from the checked-out tree (HEAD:distribution/
  dist-manifest via git show) drives fresh vendor AND post-update
  re-application — fresh installs and migrated installs cannot diverge.
- Non-cone mode because the manifest names root FILES; cone mode
  force-materializes ALL root files (would drag TASKS.md back in).
- Manifest-less trees (published tags v0.3.x and older) vendor whole —
  published releases keep working byte-identically (DoD «история не
  переписывается» has a runtime corollary: old tags must stay
  installable). Old git without sparse support degrades to full checkout
  with an honest log line — degraded, never broken.

## Justification C — qroky.sh owns entry only, install.sh owns logic

Reinstall/orphan/recovery logic from ATOM-106 is NOT duplicated: qroky.sh
maintains the kit copy (~/.qroky/kit on the latest release tag; occupied
non-git folder = honest message, not git fatal) and execs install.sh.
Uninstall installer resolution chain: kit copy → the instance's own
vendored framework/distribution/install.sh (ships by manifest — works
offline) → polite no-op. Install location resolution for uninstall/update
uses the machine trace, never the clone path (DoD 5 verbatim; scenario 21
kills the clone pointer to prove it).

## Justification D — lab publication path

Mandate offered two paths; chose «prepare locally bare-ready, coordinator
pushes»:
- CEO's sensitivity review of decisions/ is an explicitly PARALLEL
  human-task (constraint 6). A public push of ~580 history files BEFORE
  that review completes is an irreversible action taken while its
  precondition is still open — strictly worse than a one-command delay.
- gh auth exists and was within gate scope; not using it here is a
  deliberate sequencing choice, not an E1 block.
- Local repo is push-ready: single commit 842446d, README with two-houses
  + workflow + history note, .gitignore. Refresh-at-cut documented in
  RESULT (my own 130 records postdate the snapshot).

